    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the \"goblin\" confusion! You are absolutely right; I was just trying to be as vivid as a goblin could be, but I forgot to translate that into plain English for you. No need for the fantasy metaphors, just straight-up culinary science.\n\nHere is exactly how to fix your separated hollandaise so you can enjoy brunch:\n\n1.  **Stop the Heat Immediately:** Turn off the burner. If the sauce is already separated, adding more heat will only make the proteins tighten up and the oil separate further.\n2.  **Add a Liquid:** Pour in a splash of warm milk, cream, or even a little water. This helps break the tension between the fat and the egg proteins.\n3.  **Stir Vigorously:** Use a whisk or a spatula to stir the mixture constantly. You need to keep the fat suspended in the liquid.\n4.  **Reheat Gently:** If you must reheat it, do so very slowly over low heat, stirring continuously. Do not let it boil.\n5.  **Strain It:** Pour the mixture through a fine-mesh sieve into a bowl lined with cheesecloth. This removes the separated oil and",
      "source": "target",
